h3. Summary

When adding a post function that updates the status and issue type via:

{code}
workflowManager.migrateIssueToWorkflow(issue, workflowManager.getWorkflow(issue.getProjectId(), newIssueTypeId), status);
{code}

the transition history from the current status to the new one does not reflect in the history tab.

*Steps to replicate*
# Setup Jira Software 7.10.0 with "Update on Transition for Jira" app installed. This will update the status from "Others" to "Task". Others in this case are all issue type not Task
# Setup 2 workflows: (refer to screenshot)
## Task (Under Review -> Open -> In Progress -> Done)
## Others (Review -> In Progress -> Resolved)
# Add post function in "In Progress" of "*Others*" Workflow, such that: _Update the issue type to TASK and status to OPEN when the issue is transitioned to In Progress._ (see screenshot)
# Create a Bug ticket and transition this to In-Progress to trigger the post function and change the status
# Notice that only the "Under Review -> In Progress" is listed here but not the "In Progress -> Open"

Possible culprit:
It looks like the migration changes are missing from the {{transientVars.get("changeItems")}}:

{code:title=GenerateChangeHistoryFunction}
public void execute(Map transientVars, Map args, PropertySet ps) {
        MutableIssue issue = (MutableIssue)transientVars.get("issue");
        IssueChangeHolder changeHolder = new DefaultIssueChangeHolder();
        if (transientVars.get("changeItems") != null) {
            changeHolder.setChangeItems((List)transientVars.get("changeItems"));
        }

        issue.setUpdated(UtilDateTime.nowTimestamp());
        Map<String, ModifiedValue> modifiedFields = issue.getModifiedFields();
        if (!modifiedFields.isEmpty()) {
            FieldManager fieldManager = ComponentAccessor.getFieldManager();
            Iterator var8 = modifiedFields.keySet().iterator();

            while(var8.hasNext()) {
                String fieldId = (String)var8.next();
                if (fieldManager.isOrderableField(fieldId)) {
                    OrderableField field = fieldManager.getOrderableField(fieldId);
                    FieldLayoutItem fieldLayoutItem = ComponentAccessor.getFieldLayoutManager().getFieldLayout(issue).getFieldLayoutItem(field);
                    field.updateValue(fieldLayoutItem, issue, (ModifiedValue)modifiedFields.get(fieldId), changeHolder);
                }
            }

            issue.resetModifiedFields();
        }

        Issue originalIssue = (Issue)transientVars.get("originalissueobject");
        ((IssueUpdater)ComponentAccessor.getComponentOrThrow(IssueUpdater.class)).silentlyUpdateIssueNoHistory(originalIssue, issue, changeHolder.getChangeItems());
        if (!changeHolder.getChangeItems().isEmpty()) {
            ApplicationUser user = WorkflowUtil.getCallerUser(transientVars);
            GenericValue changeGroup = ChangeLogUtils.createChangeGroup(user, issue.getGenericValue(), issue.getGenericValue(), changeHolder.getChangeItems(), false);
            transientVars.put("changeGroup", changeGroup);
            Object historyMetadata = transientVars.get("history_metadata");
            if (historyMetadata instanceof HistoryMetadata) {
                ((HistoryMetadataManager)ComponentAccessor.getComponentOrThrow(HistoryMetadataManager.class)).saveHistoryMetadata(changeGroup.getLong("id"), user, (HistoryMetadata)historyMetadata);
            }
        }

    }
{code}

h3. Summary

The REST API entry point (POST):
 {{/rest/api/2/reindex}}
does not consider the data sent via POST, it does expect parameter instead (in a form specific to GET method)
h3. Steps to reproduce
{code:java}
data="type=FOREGROUND&indexComments=true&indexChangeHistory=true&indexWorklogs=true"

curl -u ${username}:${password} -X POST --data "${data}" "${jira}/rest/api/2/reindex"
{code}
h3. Expected result

Response: HTTP/1.1 20X
and JSON result with updated data (action submitted).
h3. Actual result

Response: HTTP/1.1 415
and no data (no submitted action in result).
h3. Current implementation
{code:java}
data="type=FOREGROUND&indexComments=true&indexChangeHistory=true&indexWorklogs=true"

curl -u ${username}:${password} -X POST "${jira}/rest/api/2/reindex?${data}"
{code}
HTTP/1.1 202
JSON:
{code:java}
{"progressUrl":"/secure/admin/jira/IndexProgress.jspa?taskId=10108","currentProgress":0,"type":"FOREGROUND","submittedTime":"2018-08-03T12:37:06.631+0200","success":false}
{code}

Created from [https://getsupport.atlassian.com/browse/GHS-118026] where customer followed instructions from [this|https://confluence.atlassian.com/pages/viewpage.action?pageId=939707304] article on how to configure JMX monitoring for JIRA and it didn't work.

Having investigated the issue, the following *workaround* was suggested by support and implemented successfully by customer:
{panel}
1) Stop JIRA

2) Add the following to setenv.sh:
{code:java}
CATALINA_OPTS="${GC_JVM_PARAMETERS} -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.port=8099 -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.authenticate=false -Dcom.sun.management.jmxremote.ssl=false ${CATALINA_OPTS}"
{code}
3) Start JIRA

4) Access JMX Monitoring page in JIRA and re-enable JMX monitoring

5) Start jconsole, navigate to com.atlassian.jira and expand it.
{panel}
Customer also expressed a concern that instructions to restart JIRA are not included in the article.
